Semilarski v. Prosecutor: the cassation of the former deputy mayor of Tartu will be considered on August 4
This means that a decision on it is likely to be taken in early September.
The courts of the first two instances refused to hear Semilarski's lawsuit, but in April his appeal of cassation was accepted in the proceedings by the State Court.
On 12 December 2019, the Tartu Administrative Court returned the complaint to the applicant, as its authorization does not fall within the jurisdiction of the administrative court.
The court order indicated that the complaint contained a claim for compensation for damages caused in the course of criminal proceedings.
“The prosecutor’s office and the county court should regulate such matters,” Annette Kreitsmann, a spokeswoman for the Tartu courts, told ERR.
According to her, Valvo Semilarski appealed this decision to the district court, which on February 5 did not change the decision of the court of first instance.
The state will now have to say its word.
According to Semilarski's lawyer, Oliver Nyaes's lawyer, his client was unreasonably suspected of bribery for about two years.
Now he demands that the prosecutor’s office refute the false allegations against him and reimburse him for moral damages.
The reason for the complaint to the court was the statements of the prosecutor in the special cases of the Lyuna District Prosecutor’s Office of Margus Gross, made by him in October 2017, when Semilarski, together with another at that time Deputy Mayor of Tartu Artem Suvorov, was arrested on suspicion of non-commitment.
“Remember that when I was arrested, the Security Police and the Prosecutor’s Office immediately held a press conference and informed the entire Republic of Estonia that the leaders of Tartu – one of the most influential bodies of local government – are selling.
These public suspicions hanging in the air have accompanied me for about two years.
And now that these allegations and suspicions have turned out to be false, the prosecutor’s office does not want to say anything about it,” Semilarski said in early August 2019.
According to Oliver Nyaes, at a press conference, the prosecutor went beyond the legal framework in which the prosecutor’s office should operate.
“The allegation of bribery and bribery turned out to be false, but that’s not the only problem here.
The European Court of Human Rights, for example, has repeatedly stressed in its rulings on Russia, as well as on Lithuania, that at the stage of the investigation, state representatives should be careful when choosing words so that the suspects would not be represented as criminals before the sentencing.
The prosecutor’s office is also bound by the presumption of innocence, which unfortunately has not been observed in this case against Valvo Semilarski,” Nyaes said.
"Semilarski's public presentation as a serious offender and briber in circumstances where the facts underlying the suspicion of bribery are still being ascertained is unacceptable, which contradicts the presumption of innocence and is unfair to the plaintiff."
According to rus.err.ee, former deputy mayor of Tartu, Valvo Semilarski, will not be prosecuted on bribery charges - the criminal case against him in July was partially closed.
At the same time, the former official is tried on charges of knowingly violating anti-corruption legislation when conducting transactions in particularly large sizes.
According to the indictment, between 2015 and 2017, the former deputy mayor of Tartu participated more than thirty times in meetings of the city administration in making decisions related to companies operating in Tartu, with the owners or managers of which Semilarski actively communicated at a personal level in the city.
According to Gross, in all these cases, Semilarski had personal interests, and therefore he had to abstain from participating in decision-making.
Earlier, according to rus.err.ee, the prosecutor's office presented Semilarsky's suspicions of receiving bribes and violations of anti-corruption legislation when conducting transactions in particularly large sizes.
This happened in October 2016, when he was detained along with another deputy mayor, Artem Suvorov (Centrist Party).
The prosecutor’s office and the security police said there was strong evidence against the two deputies.
After that, both officials resigned.
Suvorov’s case later came to the court, which fully justified the policy.
The trial in the case of Valvo Semilarski is still ongoing.
