How the ECB’s decision to reduce the key rate will affect the economy
The Bank of Russia is expected to lower the key rate again.
It fell by a further 0.25 percentage point, to 4.25% per annum - formally the next historical minimum.
Judging by the return of a short step of the rate cut, as well as the tonality of the ECB’s statements and updated forecasts on the Russian economy, the regulator looks at the economic outlook more optimistic than before.
This means that the current cycle of monetary policy easing may soon come to an end.
“We continued to soften monetary policy, primarily considering that the risks of inflation offset down from 4% in 2021 remain,” the head of the Bank of Russia, Elvira Nabiullina, said in a statement.
They are associated with a significant decrease in economic activity, a decline in domestic and external demand.
The recovery of the economy, according to Nabiullina, will take more than one and a half years.
At the same time, she noted that after the lifting of restrictions due to the pandemic, economic processes resumed: energy consumption, consumer and investment demand were restored, construction and production of consumer goods expanded, annual rates of decline in freight turnover of transport, industrial production slowed down.
According to the ECB’s forecast, the economy will shrink by 4.5-5.5% in 2020 (previously expected to shrink by 4-6%), and the recovery growth in 2021 will be 3.5-4.5%, while in 2022 it will shrink by 2.5-3.5%.
In addition, the Bank of Russia revised its forecast for annual oil prices to $38 and $40 per barrel of Urals in 2020 and 2021, respectively.
Earlier, the central bank expected $27 and $35 per barrel.
Finally, the Bank of Russia’s inflation forecast for 2020 was 3.7-4.2% against the previously expected 3.8-4.8%.
The view of the Bank of Russia on the situation in the economy is becoming more optimistic, which brings us closer to the end of the easing cycle, according to economists for Russia and CIS "Renaissance Capital" Sofia Donets and Andrey Melashchenko.
Thus, the Bank of Russia consistently lowers the key rate more than a year, since the beginning of last summer it has already fallen by 3.5 percentage points.
And at the last meeting in June, the Central Bank immediately lowered it by one percentage point due to the low rates of inflation due to suppressed demand and the need to stimulate the slowing economy due to the pandemic and the associated constraints.
Chances of pre-adjusting monetary policy remain (at the next meeting on September 18 and until the end of the year), but the limit is already close, agrees the chief analyst of the Rosbank, Yevgeny Koshelev.
The combination of pro-inflation risks also indicates a pause in easing interest rates – disrupted supply chains, possible cost increases due to epidemic prevention measures and a faster (compared to expected) recovery in demand, he says.
In addition, the Bank of Russia’s follow-up will require more attention to inflationary processes during the harvest season, as well as external volatility, which has increased against the background of geopolitical conflicts, Koshelev said.
In one way or another, the reduction of the key rate will lead to further reductions in rates for the most reliable borrowers, as well as, perhaps, on the mortgage, says the senior economist of the analytical management of the Bank "Opening" Maxim Petronevich.
The adjustment of the rates will be less pronounced than the reduction of the key rate, he clarifies.
Rates on demand loans may fall by another 0.3-0.6 percentage point during the second half of the year, mortgage rates can end the year in the range of 6.2-7%, does not exclude economist "BKS Prime Minister" Anton Pokatovic.
The average interest rates on deposits, in his opinion, will also fall - in the coming months they can fall to 4.2-4.5% (now just above 4.5%).
