Rwandan man admits to burning cathedral in Nantes
A Rwandan man, who worked at St. Peter and Paul’s Cathedral in the French city of Nantes on a voluntary basis, confessed to his burning a week after the fire.
This was reported on Sunday by France-3 TV channel.
According to him, the man, who had already been detained on July 19, the day after the fire, was detained again the day before.
On Saturday night, he appeared before the investigating judge.
After being charged with deliberate damage to property, the man admitted that he had organized fires in three places - under a large organ, under a small organ and near an electric shield.
He is now facing up to 10 years in prison and a <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>150,000 fine.
The motives of the 39-year-old Rwandan have not yet been disclosed.
It is only known that he volunteered to help in the cathedral and on the day of the fire had to close its doors.
However, according to footage from CCTV cameras, he left the religious institution 15 minutes after receiving calls about a fire in the building.
The burning of the cathedral of Saints Peter and Paul took place on July 18.
More than 200 firefighters fought for several hours for a monument of Gothic architecture.
However, they failed to save the stained glass windows of the time of Louis XII and the unique organ of the Baroque era.
The situation could only be brought under control three hours after the start of the fire.
As a result of the incident, no one was injured.
The fire was not the first in the temple’s existence.
In 1972, a fire destroyed his roof.
It took 13 years to eliminate the effects of that fire.
For parishioners, the cathedral was reopened only in 1985.
